String txt_Bauer_Amalia_en = "Josef Bauer and his wife Ernestine lived in the street “Hauptstraße” with their two children, not far away from his brother Simon and his wife.\nThe two brothers led a business which focused on trade on commission and had been established by their father, Moses Bauer, who had migrated to Erlangen. Over the course of time they expanded the business and temporarily traded with horses, wood and cattle.\nWhen Amalie Bauer was expecting her first child, Lotta, in 1923, the two children of her husband’s brother were already 10 and 13 years old.\nIn the first years of national socialism in Erlangen, the two families struggled greatly because of harassment. Their business was denounced numerous times, but the proceedings were stopped due to a lack of evidence in all cases. In addition, they suffered under the changing environment in their private life. Because of that they moved to Munich in 1938, in order to plan their emigration to the Republic of.\nOne year later Josef, Ernestine, Simon and Amalie Bauer drove to Hamburg with their children and boarded the ship “St. Louis”. The St. Louis was to bring them to Havana, Cuba, alongside 933 other Jewish refugees. Unfortunately national socialism had already spread to Cuba and thus the St. Louis was permitted to berth. Even though the captain tried to negotiate with Florida to let the refugees enter the United States of America and the affair was discussed on an international level, the ship had to return to Europe. Finally Great Britain, France, Belgium and the Netherlands agreed to give the passengers refuge, but Josef and Simon Bauer chose to return to Munich with their families instead.\nOn the 20th of November 1941 Josef, Simon and their wives were deported to Kaunas, Lithuania. Five days later they were murdered in the local concentration camp.";

