String txt_Cohn_Alfred_en = "Alfred Cohn was born on the 3rd of April in Schönlake, Poland, where he lived with his parents Siegmund and Amalia.\nIn 1910 he moved from the city of Karlsruhe to Erlangen. One year later he established a shop for lingerie and woollen goods which became a wholesale trade in 1921.\nIn 1938 he had to move his shop from the Adolf-Hitler-Straße to the Einhornstraße due to the increasing restrictions by the National Socialist regime. The house was owned by Thekla Wassermann, the daughter of the deceased Jewish master butcher Salomon Wassermann and his wife Sophie.\nA few months after the move, he was forced to deregister the shop.\nAlfred Cohn was a member of the Jewish religious community from 1927 to 1932. On the 6th of January 1939 he took his own life by jumping into the river Regnitz. His grave is located in the Jewish cemetery of Erlangen.";

String txt_Cohn_Rosa_en = "Rosa Cohn was born in 1887 in Diersburg in Baden-Württemberg. She moved to the Adolf-Hitler-Straße 58 in Erlangen in 1922, so she could live with her husband to be, Salomon Cohn, and his brother Alfred. They got married one year later.\nBecause of the increasing suppression by the Nazi regime, Rosa and Salomon Cohn moved to Berlin in 1939. At the age of 55 she was murdered in the concentration camp Auschwitz.";

String txt_Dreifuss_Adolf_en = "Adolf Dreifuß was born on 6th of july 1859 in Heßloch near Worms. He was registered in Erlangen from February 7th 1907 to December 12th 1938. At the age of 23 he married Julia Laubert, born January 8th 1859, whose parents were merchants from Bruck, a part of Erlangen. In 1883 their daughter Regina was born and five years later Julia gave birth to their son Alfred.\nAdolf conducted a shop which specialised in clothing, household linen and giftware and had been founded by his father-in-law. In 1895 Julia was pregnant again, this time with the twins Sofie and Benno, but unfortunately Sofie was born dead and Benno died one week after her.\n16 years later, in 1911, Adolf had to come to terms with the death of another family member, when his wife Julia died\nFrom 1916 to 1924 Adolf Dreifuß was chairman of the Jewish religious community, three years later he retired and lived as a man of private means.\nDuring the Pogrom Night of 1938 he was still residing in Erlangen with his housekeeper Bertha Fleischhauer, but soon after he moved into the Israelite retirement home in Würzburg. There is a good case to believe that he didn't move there voluntarily.\nOn the 23rd of September 1942 he was deported to the concentration camp near Theresienstadt and pronounced dead in December of the same year. As he was never properly buried, there is a gravesite for him on the Jewish cemetery in Erlangen.";

String txt_Fleischhauer_Bertha_en = " Bertha Fleischhauer was born on 13th of July 1879 in Adelsdorf and worked as Adolf Dreifuß’s housekeeper. There is little information about her childhood, but presumably her life was very restricted after Hitler’s seizure of power. In 1938 she accompanied her employer, when he moved to Würzburg in 1938. On 24th of March 1942 she was deported to the concentration camp Izbica in Poland. It is a moral certainty that she died there before the war was over, but her official status is “missing”.";

String txt_Heyer_Gustav_en = "Gustav Heyer was born in 1889 in the city of Halle an der Saale.\nIn 1918 he moved to Erlangen, supposedly to live with his wife Katharina. He was a trained mechanic, but later became the head of a soap business. Katharina and Gustav had six children, the first one being their daughter Katharina, who was born in 1919 and followed by her younger sister Maria one year later. Gustav’s wife gave birth to a stillborn child in 1923, nevertheless two years afterwards their daughter Margarete was conceived. The youngest daughter Johanna and their two sons Kurt and Manfred were born between 1928 and 1936.\n\nIn 1922 Gustav Heyer converted to a Jehovah’s Witness and founded the first church for adherents of his belief in Erlangen, which was prohibited in 1932. Moreover he was deprived of his citizenship and thus lost his rights. Then he was taken into custody and condemned by the regional appeal court of Nuremberg-Fürth. Following that Gustav was put into prison. Directly after he was released, he was imprisoned by the National Socialist secret service “Gestapo” and deported to the concentration camp near Dachau. There he was given the prisoner number 1257 and accommodated with other Jehova’s Witnesses. After having been transported between the concentration camp Dachau and the concentration camp Mauthausen various times, in 1942 Gustav Heyer was moved to the castle of Hartheim near Linz in Austria and murdered in the gas chamber.";

