String txt_Rotenstein_Jenny_en = "Jenny Rotenstein was born in 1869 in Maßbach near Bad Kissingen. She was the daughter of Louis and Lina Katzenberger and had three siblings.\nIn 1891 she married Samuel Weglein who worked as a merchant for her brother's enterprise. Due to the fact that nothing is known about her profession, there is a good case to believe that she was a housewife.\nBecause of their religious beliefs, she and her husband were deported to the concentration camp near Theresienstadt in 1942. Officially she died there because of a gastroenteritis, an infection of her intestines, but like many other inmates she was probably murdered.";

String txt_Rotenstein_Simon_en = "Simon Rotenstein was born on the 19th of March 1899 in Cherson, Ukraine. Many jewish people became victims of suppression even before Adolf Hitler's seizure of power. He commited suicide at the age of 34.  His death might have been crucial for his mothers decision to finally sell the family business along with their house in the Nürnberger Straße 3. Simon Rotenstein is sepulchred on the Jewish cemetery in Erlangen.";

String txt_Rotenstein_Sophie_en = "Sophie Rotenstein was born on the 28th of July 1872 in Borislav, Russia. She grew up in her home town and got to know her future husband, a cigarette and cigar manufacturer, there as well. They got married in 1893 and had their first child, their daughter Fanny, four years later.\nWhen Fanny was two years old, they moved to Cherson in the Ukraine and had another child in 1899, their son Simon. During the next five years the family grew again two times, when the second son Emil and the second daughter Sinna were born.\nSoon after Sinna's birth Sophie Rotenstein and her family moved to Germany, to Erlangen to be exact. In August of 1907, three years after their arrival, Sophie gave birth to another son, who she named Albert. Her youngest child, her daughter Jenny, was born in 1912.\nSophie's husband Georg died in 1932 and only one year later, her son Simon took his own life. This might have been crucial for her decision to sell the family business along with their house in the Nürnberger Straße 3.\nShe and her daughter Jenny were deported to Czechoslovakia to the concentration camp near Theresienstadt on the 10th of September 1942. She died there the same year the camp was freed by the Allies.\nAs she has not had a proper funeral, there is a grave reserved for her at the Jewish cemetery in Erlangen. In Addition there is an inscription on her husband's tombstone.";

String txt_Uhlfelder_Frieda_en = "Joseph Uhlfelder was born on the 21st of June in 1881 in Dormitz. Two years later, his future wife Frieda Flink was born in Altenmuhr near Weißenburg-Gunzenhausen. Both of them were Jewish.\nThey got married in 1905 in Nuremberg and moved to Erlangen six years later with their children Karonine and Martin. In November of the same year, Frieda gave birth to her third child, Fanny, who sadly died one year later. In 1916, her last child, Wilhelm, was born. The family lived with Frieda’s brother Josef Flink who was deaf-mute.\nLike many other Jewish citizens, Joseph Uhlfelder fought for Germany during World War I. Nevertheless, from 1934 on, the Jewish cattle trade was largely restricted, even though there were twice as many Jewish cattle traders as non-Jewish ones. The family of Joseph Uhlfelder was one of the three remaining cattle trade families owning a paper of legitimisation for cattle trade.\nKarolina Uhlfelder, the oldest daughter, got married to Arthur Stern in 1934 and had two sons with him, Peter and Samuel. The Sterns were imprisoned in 1941 and brought to Riga. They had to work in the local ghetto and assort and package the objects of value that belonged to the prisoners.\nDuring the Night of the Broken Glass, Martin, who lived in Nuremberg by this time, hurried back to Erlangen in order to look for his parents. Unfortunately he was taken into preventive custody before finding them. He was not allowed to leave prison until a few days before Christmas of the same year.\nThree days after receiving his exit visa in 1939, the Second World War started. Therefore, Martin was forced to flee to England over different cities such as Frankfurt, Köln, Aachen and Brüssel. In 1940 he was shipped to Canada and detained in an internment camp until 1942.\nHe found employment in Montreal, where he got to know his wife. In 1954 Martin and his family moved to his brother, who was living in West Palm Beach/n.Joseph and Frieda Uhlfelder were arrested in 1941 and brought to Fürth. Frieda’s brother Josef died in the concentration camp of Sachsenhausen on the 29th of May in 1942.\nIn the same year, Frieda and her husband Joseph were deported to the concentration camp near Theresienstadt. There, Frieda allegedly died of gastroenteritis. Joseph, too, was murdered there on the 31st of March in 1944 and cremated a few days later.";

String txt_Uhlfelder_Josef_en = "Joseph Uhlfelder was born on the 21st of June in 1881 in Dormitz. Two years later, his future wife Frieda Flink was born in Altenmuhr near Weißenburg-Gunzenhausen. Both of them were Jewish.\nThey got married in 1905 in Nuremberg and moved to Erlangen six years later with their children Karonine and Martin. In November of the same year, Frieda gave birth to her third child, Fanny, who sadly died one year later. In 1916, her last child, Wilhelm, was born. The family lived with Frieda’s brother Josef Flink who was deaf-mute.\nLike many other Jewish citizens, Joseph Uhlfelder fought for Germany during World War I. Nevertheless, from 1934 on, the Jewish cattle trade was largely restricted, even though there were twice as many Jewish cattle traders as non-Jewish ones. The family of Joseph Uhlfelder was one of the three remaining cattle trade families owning a paper of legitimisation for cattle trade.\nKarolina Uhlfelder, the oldest daughter, got married to Arthur Stern in 1934 and had two sons with him, Peter and Samuel. The Sterns were imprisoned in 1941 and brought to Riga. They had to work in the local ghetto and assort and package the objects of value that belonged to the prisoners.\nDuring the Night of the Broken Glass, Martin, who lived in Nuremberg by this time, hurried back to Erlangen in order to look for his parents. Unfortunately he was taken into preventive custody before finding them. He was not allowed to leave prison until a few days before Christmas of the same year.\nThree days after receiving his exit visa in 1939, the Second World War started. Therefore, Martin was forced to flee to England over different cities such as Frankfurt, Köln, Aachen and Brüssel. In 1940 he was shipped to Canada and detained in an internment camp until 1942.\nHe found employment in Montreal, where he got to know his wife. In 1954 Martin and his family moved to his brother, who was living in West Palm Beach/n.Joseph and Frieda Uhlfelder were arrested in 1941 and brought to Fürth. Frieda’s brother Josef died in the concentration camp of Sachsenhausen on the 29th of May in 1942.\nIn the same year, Frieda and her husband Joseph were deported to the concentration camp near Theresienstadt. There, Frieda allegedly died of gastroenteritis. Joseph, too, was murdered there on the 31st of March in 1944 and cremated a few days later.";

String txt_Vissing_Hildegard_en = "Hildegard Cäcilie Laink-Vissing was born on the 9th of December in 1896. She visited a school for girls for four years and owned a driving licence.\nHer family owned a photography shop called “Photographische Kunstwerkstätte S.Katz” in which she worked until 1938.\nIn 1916 she married the merchant Paul Kornelius Johannes Laink-Vissing and became pregnant with their daughter Clara the same year. From then on, the small family lived in Hauptstraße 17.\nDuring the Night of the Broken Glass, people who were passing by broke into their shop and stole cameras and photography supplies. Hildegard and Clara were taken into preventive custody and like many other Jewish women and children, they were brought to the city hall’s patio. One month later, Hildegard had to return her driving licence - the family’s photography shop was Aryanised in 1939.\nIn the same year, she received a new card of identity that stated her profession as “merchant’s wife”. Moreover a few of her external features were listed: her annulary and auricular finger were missing, her middle finger was stiff and she had a noticeable curvature of the spine.In 1939 Hildegard got divorced and thus her ex-husband moved to Nuremberg with her daughter. One month later Paul committed suicide. The year after that, Clara moved to Freiburg with her husband, where she was killed during an airstrike.Hildegard was the last remaining Jewish citizen of Erlangen, but she was incarcerated in August of 1943 and deported to Auschwitz. From then on, Erlangen was officially “free of Jewish citizens”.";

