String txt_Weglein_Klothilde_en = "Klothilde Weglein was born on the 1st of July in 1869 in Maßbach near Bad Kissingen.\nIn 1891 she married Samuel Weglein, who was the manager of a shop owned by her brother.\nBecause of the lack of information on her profession, there is a good case to believe that she was a housewife.\nKlothilde Weglein and her husband were deported to Theresienstadt with the transport II/25. She died there on the 7th of October in 1942 at about 4am in room 14, building Q311, allegedly because of gastroenteritis.";

String txt_Weglein_Samuel_en = "Samuel Weglein was born in 1865 in Geldersheim near Schweinfurt as the first of two children. His father Jakob Weglein was a butcher, his mother a housewife.\nIn 1891 Samuel Weglein married his wife Klothilde Weglein. One year later they had their first son, Willi. When Willi was three years old, his brother Leo was born and two years later, Klothilde was pregnant again with her son Jakob. In 1896, the youngest son, Sally, was born, followed by his sister Paula in 1902.\nWilli, Leo and Sally served in the Great War and sadly Willi lost his life on the battlefield. Sally received the Iron Cross for his service in the war.\nAfter that Samuel, Klothilde and Paula moved to Erlangen.\nThere Samuel Weglein worked in a shoe business. The enterprise was owned by his wife's brother and contained 30 stores in southern Germany.\nOver the course of the Aryanisation the business was taken away from the family in 1934 and they moved to Nuremberg. But even after they had left the city of Erlangen, the antisemitism continued as people were worried that there could still be \"Jewish money\" in the firm. This resulted in the appearance of an article in the local newspaper which stated that the company had been aryanised entirely and that there was no \"Jewish money\" left. During the Second World War Paula fled to Palestine and acquired the Palestinian citizenship, while her parents stayed in Germany.\nThey were deported to the concentration camp Theresienstadt with the transport II/25 in 1942. Samuel Weglein died there the same year.";

String txt_Weinstock_Ivan_en = "Isaak Weinstock was born on 11th of March in 1859 in Rödelmaier. As his uncle was the first Jewish citizen who was allowed to move to Erlangen, he followed him in 1895. In 1985 he married Amalie Gruber. Over the course of nine years, the couple had five children, but their only son Siegmund died at the age of two.\nTheir children received a decent education. Weinstock’s third daughter, Cornelia, visited the Marie-Therese grammar school in Erlangen and studied law in Munich, Berlin and Erlangen. She managed to flee to the United States with her sister and their families.\nIsaak Weinstock was a member of the Jewish religious community’s administration.\nHe inherited his uncle’s shop for textiles, silk goods, millinery, linen and carpets.\nIn 1935 the family felt the growing influence of National Socialism on their life. They were prosecuted, because they employed an Aryan woman, which was illegal according to the “Aryan Blood and Honour Protection Act” as she was under 45 years old.\nSadly, Amalie died in 1938 and Iwan Weinstock was forced to move into a Jewish retirement home. On the 24th of September in 1942 he was deported to Theresienstadt and died there at the age of 83 in December of the same year.";

String txt_Wild_Ignatz_en = "Ignatz Wild, the son of Isaak and Amalie Wild, was born in Dormitz near Erlangen. Just like his father he became a cattle trader and moved into a house in the Innere-Brucker-Straße 6 with his first wife Pauline Therese. They had got married in Ansbach in 1904 and had two children who they named Justin and Betty. Sadly six years later at the age of 33 Pauline died. She was buried at the Jewish cemetery in Erlangen.\nA few months later Ignatz got engaged to Paula Schiff and married her in August of the same year. They had a daughter together as well and gave her the name of Alma.Ignatz Wild served in the german army in the first world war and was honoured with the \"Eisernes Kreuz II. Klasse\". \n\nIn the second half of the 1930ies Alma and Justin took flight from the uprising Nazi regime and found refuge in the USA. Only after the second world war had ended, Justin visited Erlangen for the first time and kept paying annual visits until he died. \n\nIn 1936 Mr. Wild moved to Fürth, where his brother was living with his family. He was deported on the 22nd of March 1942 and taken to the concentration camp Izbica in Poland.";

String txt_Wild_Paula_en = "Paula Wild was born on the 20th of March in 1882. Before moving to Erlangen in 1915, she lived in the city of Geisa.\nFrom January to February of the same year, she worked as a saleswoman for household goods. Moreover she earned her money as a sales representative for soap and washing detergent until 1936.\nIn August of 1910 she married Ignatz Wild and lived with him in the Innere-Brucker-Straße 6.\nThe couple had one daughter named Alma who took flight from the National Socialist regime to the United States in 1935.\nPaula Wild was deported to Riga in 1942 and has been given the status “missing”.";